Introduction

This tutorial provides an overview of the diffMIN R package, which is designed for computing individuals’ gene regulatory networks.

For more detailed information, please refer to our paper, Reconstructing Sample-Specific Differential Gene Regulatory Networks Based on Mutual Information.

Install package

To install the diffMIN package, use the following command:

# Install the remotes package if you don't have it
install.packages("remotes")

# Install the diffMIN package from GitHub
remotes::install_github("Juan-shu/diffMIN-R", ref = "master")

Loading data

library(diffMIN)
load("./exp.rda")

Create a diffMIN_object

The diffMIN package includes an S4 diffMIN_object specifically designed to store all involved data. This object contains numerous slots, including raw data ($rawdata), discretized data ($data), degree networks ($net.DM), edge networks ($net.EM), sample information ($meta.data), dimensionality reduction information ($reduction), and intermediate networks ($IN). All operations performed on a diffMIN_object will be saved in the corresponding slots.

diffMIN is computationally intensive. Dropout and sparsity in single-cell data can affect analysis.

  1. Thus, use the pre_process() function for preprocessing. This function filters low-expression samples and probes, and selects a specific number of high-variance genes. Parameters include exp, minExpr_sample, minExpr_gene, and var.genes. minExpr_sample filters low-expression samples based on minimum detection in genes and sample counts. For instance, c(0.1,5000) indicates a sample should have at least 0.1 expression in 5000 genes, while c(0,20) indicates a gene should be expressed in at least 20 cells. var.genes selects the top 400 genes by variance.

  2. The create_diffMIN_object() function creates a diffMIN_object, initializing many empty slots for data storage. rawdata is the pre-processed data with samples as rows and probes as columns. meta.data is a data frame for sample information, which can be added at creation or later. Ensure that row names of meta.data correspond to sample names.

  3. The discretize_EM() function, based on the infotheo package, discretizes data for subsequent analysis. For details, refer to ?infotheo::discretize.

exp <- pre_process(exp)
obj <- create_diffMIN_object(rawdata = exp)
obj <- discretize_EM(diffMIN_object = obj)

Prepare network

Before computation, specify background samples. Details on background sample specification are available in our paper. Use addGroup() to add sample information to the diffMIN_object. Here, we use cardiac cells from non-surgical mice as the background.

library(stringr)
group <- colnames(obj@rawdata)[str_detect(colnames(obj@rawdata),"Sham")]
obj <- addGroup(diffMIN_obj = obj,group = group)

diffMIN uses random permutation testing to validate the network. Use prepare_network() to generate random networks. nRanNet specifies the number of random networks. For single-cell (sample) networks, random networks will be generated for each cell (sample). Testing shows that 100 random networks are sufficient. The seed parameter ensures result reproducibility.

obj <- prepare_network(diffMIN_object = obj, nRanNet = 100, seed = 1)

Compute network

Use compute_NMI_network() for network computation. diffMIN is computationally intensive; thus, multi-threading and background execution are recommended. The function includes parameters for multi-threading. type specifies whether to compute background or foreground networks.cores parameter sets the number of cores. The function will automatically identify the highest number of cores available. batch_size sets the number of cells per batch. The function also includes parameters for file saving and permutation.test.times for permutation testing, with p.value.cutoff indicating the significance level of edges, defaulting to 0.05. Note: Each process will use approximately 22GB of memory and take about 1 day, so ensure adequate computing resources to prevent server crashes.

obj <- compute_NMI_network(obj,type = "bg",cores = 7,batch_size = 30,filename = "bgnet",
                           p.value.cutoff = 0.05, whether_to_save = F,
                           use_adj.p = F)
obj <- compute_NMI_network(obj,type = "fg",cores = 7,batch_size = 30,filename = "fgnet",
                           p.value.cutoff = 0.05, whether_to_save = F,
                           use_adj.p = F)

To reduce computation time, load previously computed data directly:

load("./obj.rda")

For further exploration, use transform_EM_to_DM() to convert the edge matrix to a degree matrix.

Reduction

Next, use RunReduc() to perform dimensionality reduction on the results, supporting umap, tsne, and pca. The perplexity parameter is used for t-SNE calculation. Additional parameters for umap can be passed through ... to the umap::umap() function. The function retains only the first two dimensions. For further dimensionality reduction, extract the degree matrix or edge matrix for analysis.

obj <- RunReduc(obj,reduction = "tsne")

Visualize result

Unsupervised Clustering

The cluster() function performs clustering on dimensionality-reduced data. Users can choose from methods such as hc (hierarchical clustering) and kmean (k-means clustering) for their analysis. The clustering results will be stored in the meta.data slot of the diffMIN object.

library(ggplot2)
obj <- cluster(obj,centers = 6,reduction.use = "tsne",method = "hc")
plotDot(obj,reduction = "tsne", group.by = "cluster")+coord_fixed(1)

Sample

Use plotDot() to visualize the reduction results. Adding group information to meta.data allows for grouping in the plot. Additional plotting parameters can be passed to ggplot2::ggplot() using +.

obj@meta.data$time <- factor(rep(c("sham","d3","w1","w2","w4","w8"),
                          c(64,58,82,61,73,58)),
                          levels = c("sham","d3","w1","w2","w4","w8"))
plotDot(obj,reduction = "tsne", group.by = "time")+coord_fixed(1)

Degree

Use plotdegree() to visualize the node’s degree. Additional plotting parameters can be passed to ggplot2::ggplot() using +.

library(gridExtra)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gridExtra'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     combine
p1 <- plotDegree(obj,"Nppa",reduction = "tsne")+coord_fixed(1)
p2 <- plotDegree(obj,"Ankrd1",reduction = "tsne")+coord_fixed(1)
p3 <- plotDegree(obj,"Itgb1bp3",reduction = "tsne")+coord_fixed(1)
p4 <- plotDegree(obj,"Hn1",reduction = "tsne")+coord_fixed(1)
p5 <- plotDegree(obj,"Acta1",reduction = "tsne")+coord_fixed(1)
p6 <- plotDegree(obj,"Actc1",reduction = "tsne")+coord_fixed(1)
grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, p5, p6, nrow = 2, ncol = 3)

Edge

When using the plotHM() function to plot heatmaps, you can choose between the edge, degree, and exp parameters to visualize the analysis results. Typically, due to the presence of structural proteins, gene expression levels may not fully reflect the importance of genes. Instead, we are more interested in genes with significant changes, even if their expression levels are not very high. Therefore, scaling gene expression data is necessary. However, scaling is not as critical for node degrees, as nodes with higher degrees inherently represent stronger interactions. Thus, in this example, we did not apply scaling to the degree data.

plotHM(obj,scale = F,group.by = "time", type = "degree")
## Warning: The input is a data frame-like object, convert it to a matrix.

plotHM(obj,scale = T,group.by = "time", type = "exp")
